    dek: `The moment you cast a minor, your production changes — not a little, but fundamentally. A child actor is not a small adult actor. They're a person the law specifically protects, whose time is strictly limited, whose wellbeing is your legal responsibility, and who needs to be directed in an entirely different way. Here's the honest overview of what you're taking on, and why it's worth it.`,
    seoTitle: "Working with Child Actors: What's Different for Filmmakers | Filmmaker Genius",
    seoDesc: "Casting a minor changes your whole production — legally, logistically, and creatively. A working filmmaker on what's genuinely different about working with child actors and why it's worth it. Chapter 1 of Working with Child Actors.",
    body: `<p>New filmmakers cast a child the way they'd cast anyone else — they find a talented kid, they're delighted, and they schedule them like a normal actor. Then reality hits: there's a law about the child's earnings, a permit they need, a hard cap on how many hours the kid can be on set, a required teacher and a required guardian, a whole layer of safety obligations, and a directing challenge that's nothing like working with adults. None of this is a reason to avoid child actors — some of the greatest performances in film history have come from children, and a story that needs a kid needs a kid. But you have to go in understanding that <strong>a child on set is a different kind of production entirely</strong>, with legal, logistical, and creative demands that adults simply don't carry. This whole course is your map through those demands. This first chapter is the lay of the land.</p>

<h2>The three things that are genuinely different</h2>

<p>Everything special about working with child actors falls into three buckets, and this course is organized around them:</p>

<ul class="spec-list">
  <li><b>The law.</b> Minors are legally protected in ways adults aren't. Coogan Law protects their earnings in a trust; work permits are mandatory; child labor laws strictly limit their hours and require breaks and schooling. This is not optional paperwork — it's the law, and violating it has real consequences (Chapters 2–4).</li>
  <li><b>The welfare.</b> A production employing a minor must actively protect them. That means a set teacher, a guardian or chaperone present at all times, a heightened duty of care for their safety, and attention to their physical and emotional wellbeing that no adult actor requires (Chapters 5–7).</li>
  <li><b>The craft.</b> You cannot direct a child the way you direct an adult. Kids don't respond to the same language, can't sustain the same focus, and need a completely different approach to get a real, natural performance — especially in emotional or difficult scenes. And behind every child is a parent you have to work with (Chapters 8–11).</li>
</ul>

<p>Master those three areas and you can put a child in your film safely, legally, and beautifully. Ignore any one of them and you're risking the child, your production, or both.</p>

<h2>Why it's worth the extra weight</h2>

<p>All of that can sound daunting, and I want to be honest that it <em>is</em> more work — a child actor genuinely adds legal, logistical, and creative overhead that an adult doesn't. But here's why filmmakers take it on: some stories can only be told with a child at their heart, and a real child's presence brings something to the screen that nothing else can. There's a truthfulness and an emotional directness in a well-directed child performance that adults, with all their training and self-consciousness, often can't match. Think of how many of the films that moved you most had a child at their center — that's not an accident. When the story calls for it, the payoff is enormous. And the extra weight, while real, is entirely manageable once you understand it, which is the whole point of this course. The filmmakers who get into trouble with child actors are almost never the ones who found it too hard; they're the ones who didn't know what they didn't know — who scheduled a kid for a twelve-hour day, or skipped the permit, or tried to direct an eight-year-old with the same notes they'd give a forty-year-old, and it all fell apart. You're not going to be that filmmaker, because you're reading this. Approach a child actor with respect for the law, real care for their welfare, and the right creative tools, and you'll not only stay out of trouble — you'll get a performance that makes the whole film. The extra care isn't a burden to endure; it's the price of access to one of the most powerful things a camera can capture. Let's learn how to do it right, starting with the law that protects the child's money.</p>

<div class="pullquote">A child actor is not a small adult actor. They're a person the law protects, whose time is capped, whose welfare is your responsibility, and who must be directed entirely differently.</div>

<div class="callout">
  <div class="callout-label">◆ From the set</div>
  <p>The first time I directed a child, I made the classic mistake — I treated her like a tiny adult, gave her the same kind of notes, and scheduled her like the rest of the cast. It went badly until an experienced first AD quietly pulled me aside and walked me through what working with a minor actually requires: the hours, the teacher, the guardian, and a completely different way of talking to the kid. Once I understood it was a different kind of production, everything clicked — and she gave a performance that carried the film. The extra care isn't a hassle. It's the whole reason it works.</p>
</div>`,
