    dek: `A film set is a workplace, and when a minor works in it, a whole body of child labor law applies — rules about how long they can work, when, at what age, and under what protections. These laws exist because children have been exploited on sets, and they are not suggestions. Here's the landscape of what governs a minor on your production, and how to stay on the right side of it. (Overview only — confirm the specifics where you shoot.)`,
    seoTitle: "Child Labor Laws on a Film Set: What Filmmakers Must Know | Filmmaker Genius",
    seoDesc: "A plain-English guide to child labor laws in entertainment — the rules that govern a minor on your film set, why they exist, and the categories every production must comply with. Chapter 3 of Working with Child Actors.",
    body: `<p>Adults can, legally, agree to work brutal hours; a child cannot, and the law makes sure of it. When a minor performs on your set, they're a working child, and the entertainment industry sits within a broader framework of child labor law that exists to make sure no production ever grinds a kid down for a shot. Like Coogan Law, the specifics vary enormously by jurisdiction — the rules in California differ from New York, which differ from the UK, which differ again elsewhere — so this chapter can't give you your exact numbers. What it gives you is the <em>map</em>: the categories of rule that exist almost everywhere, so you know what to go and confirm for where you're shooting, and so you understand that these rules shape your schedule, not the other way around. On a child-actor shoot, the law sets the boundaries and your production plans <em>within</em> them. Try to plan your day first and bend the child around it, and you'll break the law and probably the kid.</p>

<h2>The categories of rule to confirm</h2>

<p>Nearly every jurisdiction regulates these areas for working minors. Treat it as your checklist to research locally:</p>

<ul class="spec-list">
  <li><b>Hours of work.</b> Strict limits on how many hours a minor can be at work and actually working, varying by age — a toddler's limit is a fraction of a teenager's. These are hard caps (covered in detail in Chapter 4).</li>
  <li><b>Time of day.</b> Rules about how early and how late a minor can work, often tied to school nights, so a child isn't shooting at midnight before school.</li>
  <li><b>Rest and meal breaks.</b> Mandated breaks and meal periods at set intervals — a minor can't be worked straight through the way an adult sometimes is.</li>
  <li><b>Schooling.</b> If the child would otherwise be in school, the production must provide education on set via a qualified set teacher for a required number of hours (Chapter 5).</li>
  <li><b>Age minimums and restrictions.</b> Rules about the youngest age a child can work, with the very youngest (infants and toddlers) having the tightest restrictions of all.</li>
  <li><b>Supervision and safety.</b> Requirements for a guardian and, often, a studio teacher or welfare worker whose job includes protecting the child's wellbeing on set (Chapters 5–7).</li>
</ul>

<h2>Build the schedule around the law</h2>

<p>Here's the practical mindset that keeps you compliant and keeps the child safe: on a shoot with a minor, <strong>the child labor rules are a fixed constraint you plan around, not a hurdle you negotiate.</strong> This flips the usual production instinct. Normally you build the most efficient schedule you can and push to get the day's work done; with a child, you start from their legal limits — how many hours they can work, when, with what breaks and how much school — and you design the shooting day so their scenes fit inside those limits with margin to spare. In practice this means scheduling the child's most important scenes early, when they're fresh and you have their hours to spend; it means being realistic that a kid gives you far fewer usable hours than an adult; and it means having a plan for when their permitted time runs out, whether that's a body double for over-the-shoulder shots, splitting their scenes across days, or simply wrapping them and shooting around them. The productions that get this wrong are the ones that treat the child like an adult in the schedule and then panic when the clock runs out mid-scene — and the temptation in that moment, to push "just a little over," is exactly the temptation the law exists to remove. Don't. The hours are not flexible, and a violation isn't just a fine; it's a child being harmed for your movie. On a professional shoot, a studio teacher or welfare worker is literally watching the clock and will stop you when the child's time is up, and you should be grateful for them. On a small shoot where that's on you, be your own clock-watcher, plan conservatively, and treat the child's legal limits as sacred. Get this right and it becomes almost invisible — a well-planned child-actor day runs smoothly precisely because the schedule was built to fit the law from the start. In the next chapter we'll get specific about the single most important of these constraints: the work permit and the strict hours a minor can work.</p>

<div class="pullquote">On a shoot with a minor, the child labor rules are a fixed constraint you plan around — not a hurdle you negotiate. The law sets the boundary; your schedule fits inside it.</div>

<div class="callout">
  <div class="callout-label">◆ From the set</div>
  <p>The best first AD I ever worked with, on a shoot with a young kid, built the entire day backwards from the child's legal hours before touching anything else. The kid's key scenes went first thing; everything that didn't need the child got pushed later; and we had a doubling plan for the moment their time ran out. The day ran like clockwork, the child was never pushed, and we got everything. That's the lesson: with a minor, the law isn't the thing fighting your schedule — the law <em>is</em> your schedule. Plan around it from the start and it disappears into a smooth shoot day.</p>
</div>`,
