    dek: `On a set with a minor, one crew member has authority over you: the set teacher. Also called a studio teacher, they school the child <em>and</em> guard their welfare and hours — and they can shut your shot down to protect the kid. New filmmakers sometimes see them as an obstacle. They're the opposite: your single most valuable ally in doing this right.`,
    seoTitle: "The Set Teacher & Studio Teacher: On-Set Tutoring for Minors | Filmmaker Genius",
    seoDesc: "What a set teacher (studio teacher) does on a film set — schooling the child, guarding their hours and welfare, and why they have real authority. A working filmmaker's guide. Chapter 5 of Working with Child Actors.",
    body: `<p>The set teacher — often called a studio teacher or on-set tutor — is a certified professional whose job is two jobs at once, and both are about protecting the child. First, they're the child's <strong>teacher</strong>: during the school year, minors are legally required to keep up their education, and the set teacher provides that schooling on set, coordinating with the child's real school so they don't fall behind. Second, and just as importantly, they're the child's <strong>welfare officer</strong>: they watch the clock on the child's hours, ensure breaks and meals happen, monitor the working conditions, and have genuine authority to intervene — up to and including stopping a shot — if the child's wellbeing, safety, or legal limits are at risk. On many productions the same person carries both hats. Either way, understand this clearly: on a set with a minor, the set teacher is not below the director in the chain of command when it comes to the child. On matters of the child's welfare and hours, <em>they</em> have the final word.</p>

<h2>What the set teacher does</h2>

<p>Their role spans education and protection:</p>

<ul class="spec-list">
  <li><b>Provides required schooling.</b> Delivers the mandated hours of education on set during the school year, keeping the child current with their home school's curriculum.</li>
  <li><b>Guards the clock.</b> Tracks the child's permitted hours, working time, rest, and meals in real time, and enforces the limits — they'll tell you when the child's time is up, and they mean it.</li>
  <li><b>Protects welfare and safety.</b> Monitors conditions for the child's physical and emotional wellbeing and can halt work that puts the child at risk. Their authority here is real, not advisory.</li>
  <li><b>Coordinates with the guardian and parent.</b> Works alongside the child's guardian (Chapter 6) as part of the team responsible for the minor on set.</li>
  <li><b>Is legally required in many places.</b> For productions employing minors during school periods, a qualified studio teacher is often mandated by law, at a set ratio of teachers to children.</li>
</ul>

<h2>Treat them as your ally, not your obstacle</h2>

<p>Here's the mindset shift that separates filmmakers who work well with minors from those who struggle: <strong>the set teacher is the best friend you have on a child-actor shoot, not the enemy of your schedule.</strong> The inexperienced director sees them as the person who keeps interrupting to pull the kid away for school or to call time, and quietly resents them. That's exactly backwards. The set teacher is the person who's carrying the legal and welfare responsibility that would otherwise land entirely on you — they're tracking the hours you'd forget, providing the schooling the law requires, and standing between your production and a violation that could sink it. When they tell you the child needs to break for school or that their hours are up, they're not obstructing your film; they're protecting your film from an illegal, unsafe situation, and protecting a child in the process. The smart move is to bring them in early and work <em>with</em> them: share your schedule so they can help you fit the child's scenes into their available hours, ask their advice on how to sequence the day around school time, and trust their read on when the kid is tiring or struggling, because they're watching the child while you're watching the frame. A good set teacher will actively help you get your shots — they know the tricks for making the most of a child's limited time, they can flag when to grab a scene while the kid is fresh, and they'll tell you honestly when you're pushing too hard. Fight them and your shoot becomes a running battle; partner with them and they become an extension of your own team, quietly solving the child-welfare problem so you can focus on directing. And on the small shoots where a set teacher may not be legally required or affordable, you inherit their entire job yourself — which is a strong argument for bringing one on whenever you can, because doing their work badly is far more expensive than paying them to do it well. Respect the set teacher's authority, welcome their interruptions, and treat them as the ally they are. In the next chapter we'll look at the other key protector of the child on set: the guardian.</p>

<div class="pullquote">The set teacher isn't the enemy of your schedule — they're carrying the legal and welfare weight that would otherwise land on you. Partner with them and they'll help you get your shots.</div>

<div class="callout">
  <div class="callout-label">◆ From the set</div>
  <p>The best studio teacher I ever worked with saved my shoot twice in one day — once by quietly telling me to grab the kid's big emotional scene <em>now</em>, while she was fresh and focused, and once by calling time before I pushed her into a meltdown I didn't see coming. She wasn't fighting me; she was reading the child better than I could and steering me toward the footage while protecting the kid. I stopped thinking of set teachers as the hours police that day. They're the person who lets you direct with a clear conscience because someone competent is guarding the child. Bring them in early, tell them everything, and listen.</p>
</div>`,
