    moduleKey: "core",
    kicker: "Core Craft",
    dek: `A minor can never be alone on a set. A parent or approved guardian must be present at all times — and their role, plus the production's own duty of care, is what keeps a child genuinely safe and well in a demanding adult environment. Here's who's responsible for a child's welfare, what welfare means day to day, and how a filmmaker builds a set where a kid can thrive.`,
    seoTitle: "Guardians, Chaperones & Child Actor Welfare on Set | Filmmaker Genius",
    seoDesc: "Who protects a child actor's wellbeing on set — the required guardian or chaperone, what welfare means day to day, and the production's duty of care. A working filmmaker's guide. Chapter 6 of Working with Child Actors.",
    body: `<p>The rule is absolute and it exists for obvious reasons: <strong>a child on a set is never unsupervised.</strong> A parent or a legally approved guardian must be present and responsible for the child at all times — not down the hall, not in the car, but present. Alongside the set teacher from the last chapter, this guardian is the second pillar of the child's protection on set, and together with the production's own duty of care, they form the safety net that lets a kid work in what is, let's be honest, an intense adult workplace. As a filmmaker, you don't provide the guardian — the family does — but you are responsible for making sure the requirement is met, for working respectfully with the guardian, and for shaping a set environment where the child is genuinely cared for, not just legally covered. Welfare isn't a box you tick; it's the felt experience of the child on your set, and you have enormous influence over it.</p>

<h2>Who protects the child, and how</h2>

<p>The child's welfare is a shared responsibility across several people and the production itself:</p>

<ul class="spec-list">
  <li><b>The parent or approved guardian.</b> Must be present at all times, responsible for the child's immediate care, and the person who can speak for the child's needs and consent on their behalf.</li>
  <li><b>The chaperone.</b> On some productions a dedicated chaperone accompanies the child, especially where the parent can't be present for every moment or where multiple children need supervising.</li>
  <li><b>The set teacher / welfare officer.</b> As covered in Chapter 5, they carry formal welfare authority alongside their teaching role and can intervene to protect the child.</li>
  <li><b>The production's duty of care.</b> The filmmaker and production bear a legal and moral duty to provide a safe, appropriate environment — this doesn't transfer to the parent just because a guardian is present.</li>
  <li><b>Practical welfare basics.</b> A comfortable, private space for the child to rest and do schoolwork away from the chaos; appropriate food and rest; protection from inappropriate content, language, and situations on set; and attention to the child not being frightened, exhausted, or overwhelmed.</li>
</ul>

<h2>Build a set where a child can thrive</h2>

<p>Meeting the legal requirement — a guardian present, a teacher on hand — is the floor, not the ceiling. The filmmakers who work brilliantly with children go further: they consciously shape the whole set environment around the fact that a child is in it. This costs almost nothing and changes everything. A set is a stressful, adult, sometimes crude place — long hours, sharp language, frayed tempers, frightening equipment, tense moments. A child feels all of that, and a frightened or overwhelmed kid can't act and shouldn't be there. So the caring filmmaker does small, deliberate things: they give the crew a quiet word to watch their language and behavior when the child is on set; they make sure there's a comfortable, calm space where the kid can retreat, rest, and do their schoolwork; they keep the child away from anything inappropriate for their age; they build in the child's breaks not grudgingly but genuinely; and they set a tone of warmth toward the kid that ripples out to the whole crew. Crucially, they treat the guardian as a partner rather than a nuisance — the parent knows the child better than anyone, and a filmmaker who listens to them, keeps them informed, and works <em>with</em> their protectiveness gets a happier child and a smoother shoot. There's a hard line to hold here too: the production's duty of care is real and does not evaporate because a parent is present. If a scene, a schedule, or a set condition isn't right for the child, it's on you to fix it, not to lean on the guardian's willingness to allow it — some parents will push their child harder than you should, and part of your duty is to protect the kid even from over-eager parents (more on that in Chapter 11). Get the welfare culture right and something wonderful happens: the child feels safe, and a child who feels safe will trust you, relax, play, and give you the performance you cast them for. Welfare and performance aren't in tension; they're the same thing. A protected, happy child on a warm set is not just the legal and ethical requirement — it's the practical precondition for the great work you're hoping to capture. Next we'll get specific about the physical safety side of that duty of care.</p>

<div class="pullquote">A child who feels safe will trust you, relax, and give you the performance you cast them for. Welfare and performance aren't in tension — they're the same thing.</div>

<div class="callout">
  <div class="callout-label">◆ From the set</div>
  <p>Before a young actor arrives, I now do one quiet thing: I gather the crew and ask them to mind their language and keep the energy calm around the kid, and I make sure there's a comfortable corner set up where the child can retreat with their guardian. It takes five minutes and it transforms the shoot. The kids relax, they trust the room, and they give me things I could never have gotten from a scared child on a chaotic set. The parent notices too, and becomes an ally instead of a worried gatekeeper. Caring for the child isn't separate from getting the performance — it's how you get it.</p>
</div>`,
