    moduleKey: "core",
    kicker: "Core Craft",
    dek: `A film set is full of hazards adults are trained to navigate — heavy equipment, electrical rigs, stunts, effects, extreme conditions. A child is not trained, is smaller and more fragile, and may not recognize danger. Physical safety for a minor demands a higher standard than for anyone else on your set. Here's how to hold that standard. (This builds on the On-Set Safety course — apply both.)`,
    seoTitle: "Child Actor Safety on Set: Keeping Minors Safe | Filmmaker Genius",
    seoDesc: "How to keep a child actor physically safe on a film set — hazards specific to minors, stunts and effects, extreme conditions, and the extra caution a kid requires. A working filmmaker's guide. Chapter 7 of Working with Child Actors.",
    body: `<p>Everything in the On-Set Safety course applies to a set with a child on it — and then you layer more caution on top, because a minor is uniquely vulnerable. Adults on a set have (or should have) safety training, an adult's judgment about danger, and an adult's body. A child has none of those. They're smaller and more easily hurt, they don't recognize hazards a crew member instinctively avoids, they're naturally curious and may wander toward exactly the thing they shouldn't touch, and they can be frightened by things that don't faze an adult. So the rule is simple and strict: <strong>whatever safety standard you hold for the crew, you hold a higher one for the child.</strong> A situation that's an acceptable risk for a trained adult stunt performer may be completely off-limits for a kid, and the burden is on you to see the set through a child's eyes and remove the danger before it finds them.</p>

<h2>The heightened hazards for a child</h2>

<p>Pay special attention to these when a minor is on set:</p>

<ul class="spec-list">
  <li><b>Set hazards at child height and reach.</b> Cables, stands, heavy flags, hot lights, electrical rigs, sharp edges — a curious kid touches and trips over things an adult steps around. Keep the child's zones clear and supervised.</li>
  <li><b>Stunts and physical action.</b> Anything with physical risk involving a child demands extreme caution, professional stunt coordination, and often a stunt double. A child should never be exposed to genuine physical danger for a shot.</li>
  <li><b>Effects, weapons, and pyro.</b> Fake weapons, squibs, fire, smoke, and any special effect need rigorous control and safety briefing appropriate to a child — and often the child kept well clear, with the effect achieved separately.</li>
  <li><b>Extreme conditions.</b> Heat, cold, water, height, long hours in the elements — a child's body handles these far less well than an adult's. Limit exposure aggressively and monitor constantly.</li>
  <li><b>Animals and unpredictable elements.</b> Animals, crowds, moving vehicles — anything unpredictable is more dangerous around a child who can't read the situation. Add layers of control.</li>
  <li><b>Fatigue as a safety issue.</b> A tired child is an unsafe child — slower, clumsier, less aware. The hours limits from Chapter 4 are a safety measure, not just a welfare one.</li>
</ul>

<h2>See the set through a child's eyes</h2>

<p>The mindset that keeps children safe is a specific kind of vigilance: <strong>constantly imagine the set from the child's point of view — their height, their curiosity, their lack of training — and remove the danger before they reach it.</strong> Adults navigate a set on autopilot, unconsciously avoiding a hundred small hazards; a child has none of that autopilot, so the set that feels routine to your crew is a playground of risks to a kid. This means assigning clear responsibility for the child's physical safety at every moment (the guardian and often a dedicated crew member), keeping the child away from the working, hazardous parts of the set except when they're needed in front of the camera, walking their path and their eye-line to spot what they might touch or trip over, and briefing the crew that a child is present so everyone raises their own vigilance. For anything with real physical risk, the default is to protect the child completely — use a double, achieve the effect separately, cheat the shot — rather than exposing the actual kid; no shot is worth a child's safety, and the industry's history has painful examples of what happens when that line is crossed. It also means never letting the pressure of the schedule erode the caution: the temptation, late in a long day, to let the tired kid do "just one more" near something risky is exactly the moment to stop, because a tired child near a hazard is how accidents happen. Lean on the set teacher and guardian here too — they're watching the child's state and safety while you're watching the frame, and they'll flag the danger you're too focused to see. And remember that a frightened child is both a welfare and a safety problem: a scared kid can freeze or bolt at the wrong moment, so keeping them calm and informed about what's happening around them (the loud noise that's coming, the effect that's about to fire) is itself a safety measure. Hold the higher standard, see the set through the child's eyes, protect them completely from real risk, and never let the clock push you into cutting a corner. A set where a child is genuinely safe is the non-negotiable foundation for everything else — and with the legal, welfare, and safety groundwork now fully laid, the rest of the course turns to the craft: how to actually direct the child and draw out the performance.</p>

<div class="pullquote">Whatever safety standard you hold for the crew, hold a higher one for the child — and never let the clock push you into cutting a corner near a tired kid.</div>

<div class="callout">
  <div class="callout-label">◆ From the set</div>
  <p>Before a child works a setup, I now physically walk their path — from their chair to their mark and back — at their height, looking for what they might touch, trip on, or be frightened by. Every time, I find something: a cable across their route, a hot light within reach, a loud effect nobody warned them about. Fixing it takes a minute. I also assign one person whose only job in that moment is the child's physical safety, so it's never "everyone's job," which means no one's. And when the day gets long and I'm tempted to squeeze the tired kid past a hazard for one more take — that's exactly when I stop. No shot is worth it.</p>
</div>`,
