    body: `<p>When you audition an adult, you're largely assessing craft — can they act, can they take direction, do they fit the role. When you audition a child, craft is almost beside the point, because most kids don't have it yet. Instead you're looking for something more elemental: is this child <em>naturally</em> the character in some essential way, are they comfortable and unselfconscious in front of you, can they play and stay present, and do they take direction in a child's way — responding to a game, a redirect, a bit of imagination. A child who "performs" a polished, over-coached audition is often a worse bet than a natural, relaxed kid who just <em>is</em> the character and lights up when you play with them. And crucially, you're also, quietly, casting the whole package around the child: the parent you'll work with all shoot (Chapter 11), and a family that understands and is ready for the legal and logistical realities. The right child for your film is the natural, present, directable one — plus a supportive family and a workable situation.</p>

<h2>What to look for when casting a child</h2>

<p>Assess these in a child's audition:</p>

<ul class="spec-list">
  <li><b>Naturalness over polish.</b> Look for a child who is unselfconsciously themselves and believable, not one performing a slick, coached routine. Realness beats technique in a kid every time.</li>
  <li><b>Presence and comfort.</b> Are they relaxed and engaged with you, or frozen and anxious? A child who's comfortable in the room will be comfortable on set; a terrified one may not cope with the day.</li>
  <li><b>Directability, child-style.</b> Give them a redirect as a game ("now try it like you're telling a secret") and see if they can take it and play. That responsiveness matters more than their first read.</li>
  <li><b>The right essence for the role.</b> Because you'll build the performance around who the child genuinely is, cast a kid whose real nature fits the character — you're casting closer to type than with adults.</li>
  <li><b>The family and situation.</b> Meet the parent, gauge whether they're supportive and realistic, and confirm the family understands the commitment, the hours, and the legal setup. You're casting them too.</li>
  <li><b>Keep auditions kid-friendly.</b> A warm, playful, low-pressure audition both treats children well and shows you the real child — a scary audition just shows you a scared kid.</li>
</ul>

<h2>Your first child-actor shoot: the whole course in order</h2>

<p>Let's bring everything together into one roadmap. Working with a child actor well is not complicated once you see the shape of it — it's law, then welfare, then craft, each handled in turn. <strong>Before the shoot,</strong> square away the legal foundation: confirm the child's work permit is valid, make sure the Coogan trust account is set up and your payroll will handle the withholding, learn the exact hours and rules for the child's age and your jurisdiction, and hire your set teacher and confirm the guardian. <strong>Build your schedule around the child's limits,</strong> not the other way around — key scenes early while they're fresh, realistic about the small window you have, with a doubling or split plan for when their time runs out. <strong>On the day,</strong> create the welfare culture that lets a kid thrive: a calm set, a comfortable space to rest and do school, a mindful crew, real breaks, and a higher safety standard than you hold for anyone else. <strong>To get the performance,</strong> forget adult acting notes — set up games the child can believe, build trust, keep it fun, feed lines and engineer real reactions, roll generously, and catch the truthful moments to assemble in the edit. <strong>For the hard scenes,</strong> access emotion through imagination and technique, never through real distress, and never cross the line of harming the child. <strong>Throughout,</strong> make the parent an ally through early, generous communication — and hold your duty of care above the parent's wishes on the rare occasion you must. Lean on your team the whole way: the set teacher and guardian carry real authority and real expertise, and they're there to help you do this right. That's the entire course, and it's genuinely learnable. The filmmakers who work beautifully with children aren't the ones with a special gift; they're the ones who respect the law, care for the child, and adapt their craft — exactly what you now know how to do. Do all that, and you get access to one of the most powerful things in all of cinema: a real child, truthfully alive on screen, in a story only a child could tell. It's worth every bit of the extra care. Now go and make it.</p>

<div class="pullquote">Working with a child actor is law, then welfare, then craft — each handled in turn. It isn't a gift some directors have; it's a process you can learn. And now you have.</div>

<div class="callout">
  <div class="callout-label">◆ From the set</div>
  <p>The best kid I ever cast gave the worst "audition" on paper — no polish, forgot half the lines — but when I stopped the reading and just played a silly game with her, she came completely alive and <em>was</em> the character, present and true. I cast her over slicker kids and never regretted it. That's the whole lesson of casting children: don't hire the best little performer, hire the realest, most present, most directable child, with a supportive family behind them. Then protect them, care for them, play with them, and catch the truth. Do that, and a child will give your film something no adult ever could.</p>
</div>`,
